Project 2 - Supervised learning:Regression¶

Title: Cars4U price prediction¶

Author: Pankaj Singh¶


Domain

Market analytics/Price prediction

Project Context

There is a huge demand for used cars in the Indian Market today. As sales of new cars have slowed down in the recent past, the pre-owned car market has continued to grow over the past years and is larger than the new car market now. Cars4U is a budding tech start-up that aims to find footholds in this market.

In 2018-19, while new car sales were recorded at 3.6 million units, around 4 million second-hand cars were bought and sold. There is a slowdown in new car sales and that could mean that the demand is shifting towards the pre-owned market. In fact, some car sellers replace their old cars with pre-owned cars instead of buying new ones. Unlike new cars, where price and supply are fairly deterministic and managed by OEMs (Original Equipment Manufacturer / except for dealership level discounts which come into play only in the last stage of the customer journey), used cars are very different beasts with huge uncertainty in both pricing and supply. Keeping this in mind, the pricing scheme of these used cars becomes important in order to grow in the market.

As a senior data scientist at Cars4U, you have to come up with a pricing model that can effectively predict the price of used cars and can help the business in devising profitable strategies using differential pricing. For example, if the business knows the market price, it will never sell anything below it.

Data Description

The data contains the different attributes of used cars sold in different locations.

Attribute Information

  • S.No. : Serial number
  • Name : Name of the car which includes brand name and model name
  • Location : Location in which the car is being sold or is available for purchase (cities)
  • Year : Manufacturing year of the car
  • Kilometers_driven : The total kilometers driven in the car by the previous owner(s) in km
  • Fuel_Type : The type of fuel used by the car (Petrol, Diesel, Electric, CNG, LPG)
  • Transmission : The type of transmission used by the car (Automatic/Manual)
  • Owner : Type of ownership
  • Mileage : The standard mileage offered by the car company in kmpl or km/kg
  • Engine : The displacement volume of the engine in CC
  • Power : The maximum power of the engine in bhp
  • Seats : The number of seats in the car
  • New_Price : The price of a new car of the same model in INR Lakhs (1 Lakh INR = 100,000 INR)
  • Price : The price of the used car in INR Lakhs

Project Objective

  • To explore and visualize the dataset.
  • Build a linear regression model to predict the prices of used cars.
  • Generate a set of insights and recommendations that will help the business.

Project Deliverables

  • Develop a pricing model that can effectively predict the price of used cars and can help the business in devising profitable strategies using differential pricing
  • Perform linear regression and deliver predictions for car prices
  • Actionable insights and recommendations that will help the business.

Learning Objective

  • Exploratory Data Analysis and insights
  • Data pre-processing
  • Linear regression : Model building \& evaluation

In [9]:
def variable_to_num(x):
    """
    This function takes in a string representing a mileage, Engine & Power.
    If the input is already numeric, which probably means it's NaN,
    this function just returns np.nan.
    """
    if isinstance(x, str):  # checks if `x` is a string
        return float(x.split(' ')[0])
    else:  # this happens when the current income is np.nan
        return np.nan

units_cols = ['Mileage', 'Engine', 'Power']
for colname in units_cols:
    cars[colname] = cars[colname].apply(variable_to_num)

def plot_countplots(data, varname, nlim=None):
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(nrows=1, ncols=1, figsize=(16,10))
    colors = sns.color_palette('Set2', data.nunique())[:data.nunique()]
    sns.countplot(data, ax=ax, palette=colors,
                  order = data.value_counts().index[:nlim])
    ax.tick_params('x', labelrotation=90, labelsize=20)
    ax.tick_params('y', labelsize=20)
    ax.set_title(f'Countplot for the categorical variable {varname}', fontsize=20)
    ax.set_ylim([0, max(data.value_counts())*1.1])
    
    # Display the %age of the unique value of the categorical variables
    total = len(data)    
    for i,p in enumerate(ax.patches):
        percentage = '{:.0f}%'.format(100 * p.get_height()/total)
        value = '{:d}'.format(p.get_height())
        xcoord = p.get_x() + p.get_width()*0
        ycoord = p.get_y() + p.get_height()#*0.01
        ax.annotate(percentage, (xcoord, ycoord), size = 20, 
                    **dict(alpha=0.9, rotation=0), color = colors[i], 
                    fontweight='bold', fontstyle='italic')

# While doing uni-variate analysis of numerical variables we want to study their central tendency 
# and dispersion.
# Let us write a function that will help us create boxplot and histogram for any input numerical 
# variable.
# This function takes the numerical column as the input and returns the boxplots 
# and histograms for the variable.
# Let us see if this help us write faster and cleaner code.
# function to plot a boxplot and a histogram along the same scale.


def histogram_boxplot(data, feature, figsize=(12, 7), 
                      kde=False, describe=False, value_counts=False, nan_counts=False,
                      bins=None):
    """
    Boxplot and histogram combined

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    figsize: size of figure (default (12,7))
    kde: whether to show the density curve (default False)
    bins: number of bins for histogram (default None)
    """
    if describe:
        print(f'Statistical distribution of the {feature} \n')
        print(data[feature].describe().T,'\n')
    
    if value_counts:
        print(f'Values and value counts of the {feature} \n')
        print(data[feature].value_counts().sort_index(),'\n')
        
    if nan_counts:
        print(f'Null values in the {feature} are : {data[feature].isnull().sum()} \n')
        
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(nrows=2,  # Number of rows of the subplot grid= 2
                                           sharex=True,  # x-axis will be shared among all subplots
                                           gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75)},
                                           figsize=figsize)  # creating the 2 subplots
    sns.boxplot(data=data, x=feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color="violet")  # boxplot will be created and a star will indicate the mean value of the column
    sns.histplot(data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins, palette="winter") if bins else sns.histplot(data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2)  # For histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(data[feature].mean(), color="green", linestyle="--")  # Add mean to the histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(data[feature].median(), color="black", linestyle="-")  # Add median to the histogram

5.1 1st Iteration of Linear Regression¶

In the very first iteration, we take the simplest approach,

  • We separate the independent variables and dependent variable
  • Convert the catgeorical variables into one-hot vector
  • Run the linear regression model
  • Evaluate the effectiveness of the linear regression model with the use of R2 values
  • #### Separate dependent and independent variables

5.2 2nd Iteration of Linear Regression¶

In the second iteration, we take the transform some of the skewed variables by taking their log10,

  • We separate the independent variables and dependent variable
  • Convert the catgeorical variables into one-hot vector
  • Do the log transformation of Price, New_Price, Age, Engine, Power and Kilometers_Driven, since they all had a right skew
  • Run the linear regression model
  • Evaluate the effectiveness of the linear regression model with the use of R2 values
  • #### Separate dependent and independent variables
In [80]:
# independant variables
X2 = CarsClean.drop(['Price', 'Model'], axis=1)

# Transform some of the variables to log and drop the original columns
X2['New_Price_log'] = np.log(X2['New_Price'])
X2['Engine_log'] = np.log(X2['Engine'])
X2['Age_log'] = np.log(X2['Age'])

Here we introduce a fucntion which first converts calculates the Price value from its log10Price value and then calculates the R2 using it.

In [87]:
## Defining this new R-Squared function which converts the log value of target variable (Price) 
# to its numerical value and calculates the R2 value
def RSquared_mod(model, X, y):

    y = np.power(10, y).to_numpy()
    yhat = np.power(10, model.predict(X))
    
    y_mean = y.mean()
    
    SST = ((y - y_mean) ** 2).sum()
    
    diff = y - yhat
    diff = diff[~np.isnan(diff)]
    SSE = (diff ** 2).sum()

    r_square = 1 - SSE / SST
    return r_square

5.5 Tuning the model in Iteration number 4 of Linear Regression¶

We deploy SequentialFeatureSelector to identify the optimal number of indepdent variables to have a good accuracy. We use the 4th model and further tune it using SequentialFeatureSelector.

Here we write two different performance evaluation functions, one for the 1st model where the Price is the variable and for the 2nd where log10Price is the variable.

In [126]:
# function to compute adjusted R-squared for 1st model
def adj_r2_score1(predictors, targets, predictions):
    r2 = r2_score(targets, predictions)
    n = predictors.shape[0]
    k = predictors.shape[1]
    return 1 - ((1 - r2) * (n - 1) / (n - k - 1))


# function to compute different metrics to check performance of 1st regression model
def model_performance_regression1(model, predictors, target):
    """
    Function to compute different metrics to check regression model performance

    model: regressor
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    """

    # predicting using the independent variables
    pred = model.predict(predictors)

    r2 = r2_score(target, pred)  # to compute R-squared
    adjr2 = adj_r2_score1(predictors, target, pred)  # to compute adjusted R-squared
    rmse = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(target, pred))  # to compute RMSE
    mae = mean_absolute_error(target, pred)  # to compute MAE

    # creating a dataframe of metrics
    df_perf = pd.DataFrame(
        {
            "RMSE": rmse,
            "MAE": mae,
            "R-squared": r2,
            "Adj. R-squared": adjr2
        },
        index=[0],
    )

    return df_perf
In [130]:
# function to compute adjusted R-squared for model with 
# log10 Price as dependent variable
def adj_r2_score(r2, predictors):
    n = predictors.shape[0]
    k = predictors.shape[1]
    return 1 - ((1 - r2) * (n - 1) / (n - k - 1))


# function to compute different metrics to check performance of a regression model with 
# log10 Price as dependent variable
def model_performance_regression(model, predictors, target):
    """
    Function to compute different metrics to check regression model performance

    model: regressor
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    """

    # predicting using the independent variables
    pred = model.predict(predictors)

    r2 = RSquared_mod(model, predictors, target)  # to compute R-squared
    adjr2 = adj_r2_score(r2, predictors)  # to compute adjusted R-squared
    rmse = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(np.power(10,target), np.power(10,pred)))  # to compute RMSE
    mae = mean_absolute_error(np.power(10,target), np.power(10,pred))  # to compute MAE
    # creating a dataframe of metrics
    df_perf = pd.DataFrame(
        {
            "RMSE": rmse,
            "MAE": mae,
            "R-squared": r2,
            "Adj. R-squared": adjr2
        },
        index=[0],
    )

    return df_perf

Summary¶

  • We have developed a linear regression model with 41 independent variables after tuning the model
  • This model is able to explain > 80% of variation in the data by making predictions on the Price of the used car
  • We have identified that,
    • Mileage, New_Price and Power have positive influence on the car Price
    • Whereas, Age, Kilometers_Driven, Fuel_Type as Petrol, Transmission as Manual and higher Owner_Type tend to negatively
    • Categorical values are slighlty difficult to interpret, but we can see that
      • A same car in some cities in southern India would be sold for a higher price than in any other part of the country.

Recommendations¶

  • The company should look into growing market in southern India
    • This is reflected from the demand of cars in southern India where 60% of cars are in the dataset
    • Also, the car Price shows a positive correlation with southern India Location
  • There is a smaller depreciation in the Price of the car with smaller number of owners. A car with many owners depreciates the Price of the car faster
  • The cars which are too old have strong price depreciation
  • Automatic Transmission cars are a growing segment and the company should keep a close eye on the business potential of the automatic cars
  • Electric cars are also going to be signifcant in the future so monitoring them would be good as the support for EV grows
  • Cars with higher Mileage and Power have a better Price compared to the lower performance cars
  • We see a trend with the Make of the car, where some lower budget cars like Maruti as well as most luxury brands BMW, Audi etc. have a positive correlation with Price
    • This indicates that the used luxury car market is popular and there is a group of richer car enthusiast who would buy them
    • Low budget cars are dominant in the market and also hold their Price well

Suggestions¶

  • The price prediction would be more accurate if there is more information on history of the car usage e.g. accidents, number of repairs etc.
  • It would make the predictions more accurate if the additional ammenities (Seats cover, AirConditioning etc.) are included in the dataset
